Translate this prisma orm query to a drizzle orm query: const user = await prisma.user.findFirst({
    select: { id: true },
    where: {
      id: userId,
      roles: {
        some: {
          permissions: {
            some: {
              ...permissionData,
              access: permissionData.access ? { in: permissionData.access } : undefined,
            },
          },
        },
      },
    },
  })
Below is one way to “translate” the Prisma query into Drizzle. (Note that the exact code will depend on your database schema and how you’ve set up your many‑to‑many relationships in Drizzle.) In this example we assume you have SQL tables for users, roles, and permissions and join tables to connect users to roles and roles to permissions (for example, “userRoles” and “rolePermissions”). Also note that while Prisma lets you “nest” filters using “some” operators, with Drizzle you typically write such a condition as an EXISTS sub‑query that joins the related tables and applies the appropriate conditions.

For example, the Prisma code

  const user = await prisma.user.findFirst({
    select: { id: true },
    where: {
      id: userId,
      roles: {
     some: {
      permissions: {
       some: {
        ...permissionData,
        access: permissionData.access ? { in: permissionData.access } : undefined,
       },
      },
     },
    },
   })

could be implemented in Drizzle roughly as follows:

---------------------------------------------------------------
import { and, eq, exists, inArray } from 'drizzle-orm';
// Assume these table objects have been defined with Drizzle:
// • users – representing the "User" table
// • roles – representing the "Role" table
// • permissions – representing the "Permission" table
// • userRoles – join table for user-to-role relation
// • rolePermissions – join table for role-to-permission relation

// First, build the subquery which asserts that the user has at least one
// role that in turn has at least one permission matching the condition.
const permissionExistsSubquery = db
  .select({ id: permissions.id })
  .from(roles)
  .innerJoin(userRoles, eq(roles.id, userRoles.roleId))
  .innerJoin(rolePermissions, eq(roles.id, rolePermissions.roleId))
  .innerJoin(permissions, eq(rolePermissions.permissionId, permissions.id))
  .where(
    and(
      // ensure the role relates to the current user
      eq(userRoles.userId, users.id),
      // Add extra conditions that come from permissionData.
      // (Assume permissionData might have other properties you want to compare.)
      /* For example, if permissionData contains a field "level", do:
         eq(permissions.level, permissionData.level), */
      // For the "access" field, we add the condition only if it exists:
      ...(permissionData.access
        ? [inArray(permissions.access, permissionData.access)]
        : [])
      // ... add any other permissionData field comparisons here.
    )
  );

// Now build the main query on the users table.
// We select only the "id" field for the first user matching these conditions.
const user = await db
  .select({ id: users.id })
  .from(users)
  .where(
    and(
      eq(users.id, userId),
      // Ensure that there exists a matching permission record through the join chain.
      exists(permissionExistsSubquery)
    )
  )
  .limit(1)
  .execute();

---------------------------------------------------------------

A few notes on the code above:

1. The EXISTS sub‑query ensures that the current user (users.id) has at least one role (joined via userRoles) that in turn has at least one permission (joined using rolePermissions and permissions) matching the conditions derived from permissionData.

2. The spread operator in Prisma (…permissionData) is “unrolled” here by explicitly listing every condition you need. In the above sample I only show the “access” condition, but you would add additional comparisons for the other permissionData fields as needed.

3. Drizzle’s query builder methods (like eq, inArray, and exists) help to build the SQL logic in a composable way. Adjust these parts, as well as table names and join logic, to match your actual database schema.

This code should give you the general approach to “translate” such nested Prisma filters into Drizzle using joins and an EXISTS clause.
